{
  "body" : "Create a vertical mid-century travel poster for {{city_name}} featuring {{landmark}}.\n\n— Strict 3-color palette (CRITICAL — only these three colors allowed) —\n  • Paper base: {{paper_tone}}\n  • Linework: technical black ink (#1A1A1A — slightly warm black, never pure #000)\n  • Accent color: {{accent_color}}\nNO additional colors. NO gradients. NO color blends. The entire image must be reproducible as a 3-color silkscreen print.\n\n— Style —\nMinimalist {{perspective_angle}} of the city, drawn in the discipline of golden-age mid-century travel posters (1950s–1960s). Reference touch-points: Sascha Maurer's New England railway posters, Alex Steinweiss album covers, Cassandre's Art Deco transport posters, Charley Harper's geometric nature illustrations, and the 1960s American National Park poster series. Premium boutique travel-brand aesthetic in the spirit of Brain Dead Studios, Standard Hotels, and Anthony Burrill prints.\n\n— Linework —\n{{linework_density}}. All linework in technical black ink with consistent stroke discipline. Show building rooftops, street grids, individual windows on key landmarks, tree canopies, river ripples, and cobblestone textures via fine hatching. The hatching gives the poster its hand-printed mid-century feel — NOT digital flat vector.\n\n— Color usage rules —\n  • {{accent_color}} is used as a SOLID FLAT FILL for the ENTIRE SKY (covering the upper portion above the cityscape's silhouette).\n  • {{accent_color}} also appears as small accents: a few rooftops, occasional street segments, the river/water surface, a vehicle or two, awnings, signs.\n  • Black hatching sits ON TOP of the cream paper base everywhere except inside the solid-color sky.\n  • Inside the solid-color sky, only the linework of clouds / birds / planes (if any) appears in black.\n  • The cream paper shows through everywhere that is not actively colored or hatched — this breathing space is essential.\n\n— Composition —\nVertical poster layout, captured in {{aspect_ratio}}. The cityscape occupies the lower 60–70% of the frame; the solid-color sky occupies the upper 30–40%, providing room for the title.\n\n{{landmark}} is the visual anchor — the largest / most central / most-detailed element of the scene, instantly recognizable. Surrounding city detail tapers in density toward the edges, creating natural framing.\n\n— Typography —\nTitle: \"{{city_name}}\" — bold geometric sans-serif (think Futura Bold / DIN Bold / Avant Garde Bold), all caps, generous letter-spacing, set in CREAM color (matching the paper base, NOT the accent color) so it sits cleanly inside the solid-color sky band. {{title_position}}.\n\nSubtitle: \"{{city_native_name}}\" — same typeface family, much smaller size, also in cream, positioned just below or beside the title with consistent alignment.\n\nAll typography must be authentic, readable, and professionally set — NO gibberish glyphs, NO distorted letters. If CJK characters are used, use a clean modern Chinese / Japanese / Korean grotesque (思源黑体 / Hiragino / Pretendard).\n\n— Style discipline —\nUltra-clean execution within the constraints. {{screen_print_texture}}. The whole poster should look like an authentic 1955–1965 vintage silkscreen travel print, faithfully reproduced — not a digital approximation, not over-stylized.\n\n— Mood —\nOptimistic, refined, timeless, premium, the romance of golden-age travel. Calm but confident. The kind of poster you'd hang in a boutique hotel lobby or a curated gallery.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT use any color outside the 3-color palette (paper / black / {{accent_color}})\n- Do NOT use gradients within the sky or any other surface — flat color only\n- Do NOT use the accent color for the title text — title must be cream (matching paper)\n- Do NOT make the linework photo-realistic — it must remain stylized hatching\n- Do NOT add modern UI elements (rounded corners, drop shadows, vector clean edges everywhere)\n- Do NOT add lens flares, glow effects, or 3D rendering\n- Do NOT generate gibberish text or fake CJK glyphs\n- Do NOT add watermarks, logos, mockup frames, or stock-illustration trademarks\n- Do NOT add a fourth color even for tiny accents (resist adding red dots, green plants, etc.)\n- Do NOT make the city look like a generic European or American template — landmarks and street patterns must read authentically as {{city_name}}\n- Do NOT crowd the title area — leave generous breathing space inside the sky band\n- Do NOT use cartoon / Disney / overly cute illustration style — keep it editorial and architectural\n\n— Output —\nVertical poster composition, ultra-detailed 8K resolution, print-ready. Indistinguishable from an authentic mid-century silkscreen travel poster, faithfully scanned and reproduced.\n\nKeywords: mid-century travel poster, vintage silkscreen, isometric bird's-eye view, fine hatching, 3-color palette, screen-print, {{city_name}}, golden-age travel, editorial illustration, boutique travel brand",
